1. Clinical Use Only
• This report is intended for informational purposes only.
• It should be used by qualified healthcare professionals for clinical correlation.
• It is not a substitute for medical consultation, diagnosis, or treatment.
2. No Diagnostic Claim
• Information in this report, including AI-based insights and trend analyses, is suggestive in nature.
• It must not be solely relied upon for diagnosis or treatment decisions.
• Always consult a registered medical practitioner.
3. Reference Ranges
• Reference ranges may vary based on age, gender, and medical history.
• They may differ from those used by other laboratories.
• Interpretations must always consider clinical context.
4. AI Interpretation Disclaimer
• AI-generated observations (if present) are based on algorithmic models trained on large datasets.
• These insights are indicative only.
• They should always be reviewed by a medical expert before any action is taken.
5. Sample Quality & Pre-Test Conditions
• Test results may be influenced by errors in sample collection or handling.
• Pre-test conditions (e.g., fasting) and patient-specific variables can affect accuracy.
• Improper handling can lead to misleading results.
6. Preventive Screening Limitation
• This report is part of preventive health screening.
• Normal results do not guarantee absence of disease.
• Abnormal results may not necessarily indicate illness.
• Further medical evaluation may be required.
7. Trend Analysis
• If graphs or historical comparisons are included, they are based only on data available within Flabs' system.
• They do not represent a complete medical history.
8. Privacy & Security

• Shared digital links or QR codes should be kept confidential.
• Flabs is not responsible for unauthorized access due to user sharing.

Plasma Glucose - Pp
This test measures your blood sugar levels after eating to assess how your body processes glucose. It helps detect
conditions like diabetes or monitor existing treatment, ensuring your blood sugar stays within a healthy range for overall
well-being.
Tooltip : Normal Abnormal Borderline
BLOOD SUGAR FASTING - 125.5 mg/dl

125.5

Common Abnormal Reasons
You might have diabetes or prediabetes. This is common in India due to dietary habits and lifestyle. Let's work on a
plan to manage your sugar intake and physical activity.
Impact On Body
High blood sugar can cause fatigue, increased thirst, and frequent urination. If not managed, it can lead to serious
complications like kidney damage and nerve problems.

Report Summary
Simplified report highlights to understand your health better.
What needs attention
High Blood Sugar Levels
Your fasting blood sugar level is 125.5 mg/dl, which is higher than normal. This could be due to your diet, lifestyle,
or other factors. As an Indian, you might be consuming more carbohydrates, sweets, or fried foods, which can
contribute to high blood sugar.
Elevated Cholesterol Levels
Your total cholesterol level is 229.8 mg/dl, which is higher than the recommended range. This increases your risk
of heart disease. Indian diets often include ghee, butter, and fried foods, which can contribute to high cholesterol.
High Triglycerides
Your triglyceride level is 268.8 mg/dl, which is higher than normal. This can be due to consuming high amounts
of sugar, refined carbohydrates, or saturated fats. As an Indian, you might be consuming more sweets, snacks, or
fried foods.
What’s Good
Good HDL Cholesterol Level
Your HDL cholesterol level is 53.2 mg/dl, which is within the normal range. This is good for your heart health, as
HDL helps remove excess cholesterol from your bloodstream.

Health Advisory
Diet and lifestyle recommendations based upon your results
Suggested Diet
Heart-Healthy Foods
Include more fruits and vegetables in your diet, such
as leafy greens, citrus fruits, and cruciferous vegeta-
bles. try to have a serving with each meal.
Eat more whole grains like brown rice, quinoa, and
whole wheat bread. these can help lower cholesterol
and control blood sugar.
Incorporate healthy fats like nuts, seeds, and av-
ocado into your snacks. these can help lower ldl
cholesterol.
Limit your intake of ghee, butter, and fried foods. try
to avoid or reduce consumption of samosas, pakoras,
and other fried snacks.
Reduce your sugar intake, especially from sweet
drinks and desserts. try to limit your consumption of
jalebi, gulab jamun, and other sweet treats.
Blood Sugar Control
Eat more fiber-rich foods like legumes, lentils, and
whole grains. these can help slow down sugar ab-
sorption and control blood sugar levels.
Incorporate protein-rich foods like lean meats, fish,
and eggs into your meals. these can help regulate
blood sugar levels.
Limit your intake of refined carbohydrates like white
rice, white bread, and sugary snacks. these can
cause a spike in blood sugar levels.
Avoid skipping meals, as this can lead to low blood
sugar levels and poor glucose control.
Lifestyle Tips
Physical Activity
Aim for at least 30 minutes of moderate-intensity ex-
ercise, such as brisk walking, cycling, or swimming,
most days of the week. try to incorporate physical
activity into your daily routine, such as taking the
stairs instead of the elevator.
Incorporate strength training exercises into your rou-
tine, such as weightlifting or bodyweight exercises, to
improve insulin sensitivity and overall health.
Avoid prolonged sitting, especially if you have a desk
job. try to take regular breaks to stand up, stretch, and
move around.
Limit your screen time, especially in the evening, as
this can disrupt sleep patterns and worsen glucose
control.
Stress Management
Practice stress-reducing techniques like meditation,
yoga, or deep breathing exercises to help manage
stress and anxiety.
Get enough sleep, aiming for 7-8 hours per night, to
help regulate stress hormones and improve glucose
control.
Avoid excessive caffeine intake, especially in the
evening, as this can disrupt sleep patterns and wors-
en stress.
Limit your exposure to electronic devices before bed-
time, as the blue light emitted can interfere with sleep.
